1. Purpose
This report documents the detection, investigation, containment, and response to a credential dumping incident involving the execution of Mimikatz on a Windows 10 endpoint within the SOC Automation Lab environment. The report covers all phases of incident response including detection, analysis, containment, eradication, recovery, and lessons learned.

2. Incident Summary
On 29 May 2026 at 04:22:28 UTC, the Wazuh SIEM detected the execution of Mimikatz, a well-known credential dumping tool, on the Windows 10 endpoint DESKTOP-VSFH4PP. The detection was triggered by Sysmon Event ID 1 (Process Creation), which was analysed by a custom Wazuh rule (ID 100003, Level 15) mapped to MITRE ATT&CK technique T1003 (OS Credential Dumping).
The attack path was as follows: the user opened PowerShell, navigated to the Mimikatz directory, and executed mimikatz.exe directly. The tool was not renamed or obfuscated, indicating either a low-sophistication attack or a testing scenario.
The SOAR platform (Shuffle) automatically processed the alert within seconds, extracting the file hash, querying VirusTotal for threat intelligence, creating a case in TheHive, and notifying the SOC analyst via email. No manual intervention was required for initial triage.

Detection Method
•	Sysmon Event ID 1 captured process creation with full metadata including file hashes, command line, parent process, and user context
•	Wazuh custom rule 100003 matched on the image path containing mimikatz.exe using PCRE2 regex
•	Alert classified as Level 15 (highest severity) with MITRE ATT&CK mapping to T1003
•	Automated SOAR workflow triggered via webhook integration within 1 second of detection

Business Impact
If this were a production environment, the execution of Mimikatz could lead to the extraction of plaintext passwords, NTLM hashes, and Kerberos tickets from memory. This would enable lateral movement across the network, privilege escalation, and potential domain compromise. In this lab environment, the impact was contained to the single test endpoint.

3. Information Exposure
Mimikatz is designed to extract credentials from Windows memory (LSASS process). If the tool was run with sufficient privileges, the following information could have been exposed:
•	Plaintext passwords for logged-in users
•	NTLM password hashes
•	Kerberos tickets (TGT and service tickets)
•	WDigest credentials if enabled
•	Cached domain credentials

In this lab scenario, the endpoint was a standalone Windows 10 machine not joined to a domain. Exposure was limited to the local user account (DESKTOP-VSFH4PP\ash).

