5. Containment

The following containment actions were taken to limit the damage and prevent further compromise:
•	Automated alert escalation via Shuffle SOAR notified the SOC analyst within seconds of detection
•	TheHive case created with full context enabling immediate investigation without additional log searching
•	File hash IOCs extracted and recorded for future blocking and detection
•	In a production environment, the recommended immediate containment action would be to isolate the endpoint from the network using EDR or by disabling the network adapter
•	In a production environment, the user account (ash) should be disabled and password reset forced for all accounts that were logged into the compromised endpoint
The automated SOAR workflow reduced the mean time to detect (MTTD) to under 2 seconds and mean time to notify (MTTN) to under 5 seconds, which in a real environment would significantly reduce the window of opportunity for an attacker to move laterally.

6. Preservation of Evidence
•	Wazuh archive logging was enabled (logall and logall_json set to yes), preserving the complete raw event data in /var/ossec/logs/archives/
•	Sysmon Event ID 1 captured the full process creation metadata including hashes, command line arguments, parent process tree, and user context
•	TheHive case preserved the alert with all associated observables, timestamps, and MITRE ATT&CK mappings
•	Shuffle execution history retained the complete workflow execution including API call results from VirusTotal
•	In a production environment, a forensic disk image of the compromised endpoint should be taken before any remediation actions
•	All evidence was timestamped in UTC for consistency across distributed systems

7. Eradication

Point of Entry

The point of entry was direct execution by the local user via PowerShell. The user navigated to the download directory containing Mimikatz and executed it manually. There was no evidence of remote delivery, phishing, or exploitation of a vulnerability to deliver the tool.
Eradication Steps
•	Remove the Mimikatz binary and the entire mimikatz_trunk directory from the endpoint
•	Scan the endpoint with an updated antivirus/EDR solution to identify any additional malicious files or persistence mechanisms
•	Check for scheduled tasks, registry run keys, and services that may have been created for persistence
•	Review Windows Event Logs for any additional suspicious activity during the time Mimikatz was running
•	Check if credential dumping was successful by reviewing LSASS access events (Sysmon Event ID 10)

Hardening Recommendations

•	Enable Windows Credential Guard to protect LSASS memory from credential dumping tools
•	Implement application whitelisting to prevent execution of unauthorised tools
•	Restrict PowerShell execution to signed scripts only using Constrained Language Mode
•	Block known Mimikatz file hashes at the endpoint protection level
•	Implement LSASS protection (RunAsPPL) to prevent direct memory access
•	Disable WDigest authentication to prevent plaintext password storage in memory

Ongoing Monitoring

The Wazuh SIEM will continue to monitor for Mimikatz execution via custom rules 100002 (Event ID 10 - Process Access) and 100003 (Event ID 1 - Process Creation). Additional detection rules should be created for renamed or obfuscated versions of the tool, as well as for other credential dumping utilities such as ProcDump, LaZagne, and secretsdump.py.

8. Recovery

Recovery steps to restore the endpoint to a known good state:
•	Verify the Mimikatz binary has been fully removed from the system
•	Force password reset for all user accounts that were active on the compromised endpoint
•	If domain-joined, reset the Kerberos TGT (krbtgt) account password twice to invalidate any stolen tickets
•	Verify that no persistence mechanisms were established by checking startup items, scheduled tasks, and registry entries
•	Confirm the Wazuh agent is active and reporting events correctly
•	Monitor the endpoint for 48 to 72 hours post-remediation for any signs of reinfection or additional compromise
•	Verify all detection rules are active and triggering correctly through controlled testing

9. Lessons Learned

What Worked Well
•	Detection was near-instantaneous. The custom Wazuh rule fired within 1 second of Mimikatz execution.
•	The automated SOAR workflow eliminated manual triage steps, reducing analyst workload significantly.
•	MITRE ATT&CK mapping on the alert provided immediate context about the attack technique and tactic.
•	TheHive case creation with full event context meant the analyst could begin investigation immediately without searching through raw logs.
•	Email notification ensured the analyst was aware of the incident even when not actively monitoring the dashboard.

What Could Be Improved
•	The detection only catches Mimikatz by filename. A renamed binary (e.g., mimi.exe or svc.exe) would bypass the current rule. Detection should also include hash-based matching and behavioural indicators such as LSASS access patterns.
•	No automated containment was triggered for this alert type. In a production environment, high-severity credential dumping alerts should trigger automatic endpoint isolation.
•	VirusTotal hash lookup was inconsistent due to the specific Mimikatz build not being in the VT database. Multiple threat intelligence sources should be queried for redundancy.
•	The workflow triggered on all level 10+ alerts initially, causing false positives from benign processes like OneDrive (rule 92910). Proper rule tuning and workflow filtering is essential.
•	No playbook existed for credential dumping incidents. A formal playbook with step-by-step investigation and containment procedures should be developed.

Recommendations
•	Develop additional detection rules for credential dumping that focus on behaviour rather than filenames (LSASS access patterns, memory dumping tools, Kerberos ticket manipulation).
•	Implement automated endpoint isolation for Level 15 alerts as part of the SOAR workflow.
•	Create formal incident response playbooks for the top 5 attack types: credential dumping, ransomware, phishing, brute force, and lateral movement.
•	Add network segmentation to limit the blast radius of a compromised endpoint.
•	Integrate additional threat intelligence feeds beyond VirusTotal (AbuseIPDB, AlienVault OTX, MISP).
•	Conduct regular purple team exercises to validate detection coverage and response procedures.
 
